---
import DocsLayout from '../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeExample from '../../../components/CodeExample.astro';

const title = '@scope and LSCSS';
const description = 'Compare native CSS @scope and Layered Semantic CSS for scoping, naming, architecture, and long-term maintainability.';

const scopeExample = `@scope (.product-card) {
    .title {}
    .price {}
}`;

const lscssExample = `.product-card {}
.product-card > .title {}
.product-card > .price {}`;

const layerExample = `@layer legacy, settings, base, utilities,
layout, components, theme, hacks;`;
---

<DocsLayout
    title={title}
    description={description}
    schemaType="TechArticle"
>
    <article>
        <p class="eyebrow">Comparison</p>

        <h1>
            @scope and LSCSS
        </h1>

        <p>
            Native <code>@scope</code> changes how much naming ceremony CSS
            needs. It gives real browser-level component boundaries without
            requiring long BEM-style element names or build-time class hashing.
        </p>

        <p>
            LSCSS supports that direction. It uses short scoped child selectors
            already, but <code>@scope</code> does not replace architecture,
            layers, state rules, or design tokens.
        </p>

        <nav class="section-nav" aria-label="Scope and LSCSS comparison sections">
            <a href="#differences">Differences</a>
            <a href="#scoping">Scoping</a>
            <a href="#architecture">Architecture</a>
            <a href="#when-to-use">When to use</a>
        </nav>

        <section id="differences" class="content-block">
            <h2>Main differences</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><code>@scope</code> provides native selector boundaries.</li>
                <li>LSCSS provides naming, layers, modifiers, and state rules.</li>
                <li><code>@scope</code> reduces selector verbosity.</li>
                <li>LSCSS defines wider architectural responsibilities.</li>
                <li><code>@scope</code> is a feature.</li>
                <li>LSCSS is a methodology.</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section id="scoping" class="content-block">
            <h2>Scoping comparison</h2>

            <p>Native browser scoping:</p>
            <CodeExample code={scopeExample} />

            <p>Current LSCSS shallow selector approach:</p>
            <CodeExample code={lscssExample} />

            <p>
                As browser support improves, <code>@scope</code> becomes the
                cleaner option. It removes some naming overhead while keeping
                ownership clear.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="architecture" class="content-block">
            <h2>Architecture beyond scope</h2>

            <p>
                Scoped selectors do not solve override order, theme ownership,
                legacy CSS, or emergency fixes. LSCSS still uses explicit layers
                for that.
            </p>

            <CodeExample code={layerExample} />

            <p>
                <code>@scope</code> improves selector boundaries. LSCSS protects
                the whole system.
            </p>
        </section>

        <section id="when-to-use" class="content-block">
            <h2>Where @scope helps most</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>modern browser support targets</li>
                <li>component-heavy interfaces needing clearer ownership</li>
                <li>teams wanting shorter selectors without weaker boundaries</li>
                <li>projects moving away from verbose BEM element naming</li>
            </ul>

            <h2>Where full LSCSS still matters</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>legacy migration work</li>
                <li>theme and token governance</li>
                <li>state, modifiers, and temporary hack management</li>
                <li>projects needing predictable full-system architecture</li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="content-block">
            <h2>Recommended reading</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><a href="/modern-css/">Modern CSS</a></li>
                <li><a href="/layers/">Layers</a></li>
                <li><a href="/naming/">Naming</a></li>
                <li><a href="/decision-trees/">Decision trees</a></li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <p>
            <code>@scope</code> is one of the best modern CSS additions because
            it removes ceremony without removing clarity. It strengthens LSCSS,
            it does not replace it.
        </p>
    </article>
</DocsLayout>
